  "aboutText": "Anthurium wendlingeri is a famous and visually stunning epiphytic subshrub native to the wet tropical forests of Central and South America, ranging from Southeast Nicaragua to Northwest Colombia. It grows with a compact crown, producing long, strap-like leaves that hang vertically. The leaves are thick, leathery, dark green, and glossy, lacking a broad heart-shaped blade. Its defining feature is the extraordinary, elongated, spiraled spadix that hangs down below the foliage in a tight spiral like a corkscrew.",
